## Session 1: React Fundamentals


```mermaid
graph LR
    JSX[JSX] -->|React.createElement| VD[Virtual DOM]
    VD -->|Diffing| DIFF[Reconciliation]
    DIFF -->|Minimal updates| DOM[Real DOM]
    ST[State Change] -->|setState / useState| VD
    PR[Props Change] -->|parent re-render| VD
```


React's mental model is a function from state to UI: `UI = f(state)`. Every re-render is React calling your component function again with new state or props.

### JSX

JSX is syntactic sugar over `React.createElement`. The JSX transformer (Babel/SWC) converts it at build time.

```tsx
// JSX compiles to:
const el = <div className="card">Hello</div>;
// React.createElement('div', { className: 'card' }, 'Hello')

// Expressions in JSX — use {}
const name = 'Alice';
const el2 = <h1>Hello, {name.toUpperCase()}</h1>;

// Conditional rendering
const Card = ({ isLoading, data }: { isLoading: boolean; data?: string }) => (
  <div>
    {isLoading ? <Spinner /> : <p>{data}</p>}
    {data && <Badge />}  {/* short-circuit — renders Badge only if data is truthy */}
  </div>
);

// List rendering
const List = ({ items }: { items: { id: string; label: string }[] }) => (
  <ul>
    {items.map(item => (
      <li key={item.id}>{item.label}</li>  // key must be unique and stable
    ))}
  </ul>
);
```

### Components and Props

```tsx
// Typed props with TypeScript
interface ButtonProps {
  label: string;
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'danger';
  disabled?: boolean;
  onClick: () => void;
  children?: React.ReactNode;
}

const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({
  label,
  variant = 'primary',
  disabled = false,
  onClick,
  children
}) => (
  <button
    className={`btn btn-${variant}`}
    disabled={disabled}
    onClick={onClick}
  >
    {children ?? label}
  </button>
);

// Composition over configuration
const Card = ({ children, className = '' }: { children: React.ReactNode; className?: string }) => (
  <div className={`card ${className}`}>{children}</div>
);

const UserCard = ({ user }: { user: User }) => (
  <Card className="user-card">
    <h2>{user.name}</h2>
    <p>{user.email}</p>
    <Button label="Edit" onClick={() => {}} />
  </Card>
);
```

### State with useState

```tsx
import { useState } from 'react';

interface Counter {
  count: number;
  step: number;
}

const CounterApp = () => {
  const [counter, setCounter] = useState<Counter>({ count: 0, step: 1 });

  const increment = () =>
    // Always use functional update when new state depends on previous
    setCounter(prev => ({ ...prev, count: prev.count + prev.step }));

  const decrement = () =>
    setCounter(prev => ({ ...prev, count: prev.count - prev.step }));

  const setStep = (step: number) =>
    setCounter(prev => ({ ...prev, step }));

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {counter.count} (step: {counter.step})</p>
      <button onClick={decrement}>-</button>
      <button onClick={increment}>+</button>
      <input
        type="number"
        value={counter.step}
        onChange={e => setStep(Number(e.target.value))}
      />
    </div>
  );
};
```

### Controlled vs Uncontrolled Inputs

```tsx
// Controlled — React owns the value
const ControlledForm = () => {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
  return (
    <input
      value={email}      // React drives the value
      onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
};

// Uncontrolled — DOM owns the value, read via ref
const UncontrolledForm = () => {
  const inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);
  const handleSubmit = () => console.log(inputRef.current?.value);
  return <input ref={inputRef} defaultValue="initial" />;
};
```

### Interview Insight

"Why shouldn't you mutate state directly?" — React uses reference equality to detect changes. If you mutate an object in place (obj.name = 'new'), the reference is unchanged, React sees no change, and no re-render occurs. Always return new objects/arrays from state updates.

